segments.text: Well, was this steam engine that was pulling the...
I'm pretty sure it was.
There's all steam back then.
Was it like a locomotive?
Yeah, but it was small, I think.
It was just a little small locomotive.
Did they use the lignite to... Yeah, fire the boilers.
Fire the boilers.
They used the lignite over here on the Gene Railroad, too.
Well, it's the Missouri Pacific now.
It used to be the I and Gene, you know.
Right.
International and Great Northern.
You see them longhorn cattle go by over there in the Carlos.
Longhorn cattle.
Yeah, the Texas coal mine was on the spur of it.
Yeah, nice empty.
But this Sanity mine over here was a...
I think they put out quite a bit of coal, too.
Santa Fe?
Mm-hmm.
Santa Fe.
Did your dad cut timber in Santa Fe?
He sure did.
He sure did, you see.
I went with him to open gates, you see.
And we'd come out back this road here and go over to where we lived.
Uh-huh.
Do you know when the Santa Fe mine was operating?
Let me ask you this.
When did your dad cut timber?
How old were you?
I was about 9, 10.
Eight, nine, ten, eleven, along there, you know.
So that would be?
I was born in 1904.
Something like that.
Oh, yes.
Did your daddy and his brother talk about the mines very much, or was most of the talk at the dinner table?
Well, that was just his brother-in-law, you know.
You see, that was his mama's, my uncle, my mother's brother that worked in the mine, you see.
My daddy's brother didn't work in the mines.
Did they talk about mining at the dinner table?
Not so much, not so much.
It was just an everyday deal with them.
It wasn't nothing unusual.
Just get the coal out.
Get the coal out and get it going.
Make that little paycheck.
Do you remember the big rains in the early 20s?
It was a big flood, I believe.
Yeah, I believe that.
I do remember that.
Did it harm your house at all?
No.
No, it didn't.
Do you remember what effect it had on the coal mines?
Coal mines?
No, I really don't remember that.
No, my granddaddy at McCoy built him a real good house.
He was a carpenter, too.
Both of my granddaddies were carpenters.
He built him a real good house.
It was a two-story.
It wasn't nothing fine, but it was good.
And he painted it.
And he had the, like I said, two-story.
And it was all right.
My daddy, he built his house, just a common old farmhouse.
But he built it good.
And it didn't damage it.
I love to tell, hear my daddy tell about though, he built a house in 1900, that's where I was born.
He built it himself out of logs and notched them, and he built the roof himself.
He arrived aboard, as he called them, and made one of them homemade roofs.
And when that 1900 flood come, hurricane, he'd say, it didn't leak a drop.
See?
Oh, so he built it down?
He built a house, you see, in the year of, you don't know, because you can't remember.
The Galveston Flood.
A hurricane.
Him and Mama, that's where I was born, see.
They lived in Galveston?
No, no, they lived over here on Grandpa McCoy's place.
He built the house himself, you see what I say.
He was so proud of it because he built it himself on his daddy-in-law's place, and he made the boards himself and put them up there.
All that rain and rain and wind coming in.
He said it didn't leak a drop.
He was so proud of it.
That's where I was born.
I can remember, of course.
People could do things back those days, you know?
Yeah, uh-huh.
They did not in such a hurry.
He could do it.
He could arrive in those boards some way with a, you know.
But you don't remember about the rains in the 1920s?
No, not really.
I thought lots of times people ought to keep a better record of a lot of things that'd be worth to them in the future, you know.
But we go along for a haphazard, you know, and don't think much about it.
For instance, some of these antiques.
That would be antiques now if we'd have saved them.
Just maybe throw them away or something, you know.
Right.
But we don't, we can't save everything.
Oh, no.
No.
That's one reason we like to do this oral history.
It's a good way to preserve the antiques.
Yeah.
What about World War I?
How did that affect Rockville?
Oh, World War I, that's a terrible thing.
We took daily paper, and every morning my granddaddy would come over there and mama would read to him.
See, he was a school teacher, but his eyes had gone bad.
She'd read to him about the war news.
We had no radios.
We did have a telephone, but we had no radios, no televisions back in World War I.
Now, you did speak of World War I.
Did you have any electricity?
No.
No.
Coal oil lamps.
Coal oil lamps.
Yeah.
Cooked with wood.
No electricity.
No running water.
No.
World War I was the same time.
It was a terrible time.
Yes.
Some of the boys right here around Milano got killed over there.
I was pretty young at the time, but I remember I wrote to one of the two of those soldiers.
Just because I knew them, not because I
And just to fast, to help it, help it.
Some of them come back, some of them didn't.
Do you remember how that... My daddy had to register in that deal.
Did any of the Mexican miners go out to fight?
I'm sure they did.
I'm sure they did.
And the black people too.
Do you remember how the mines were affected by World War I?
Did there seem to be a lot of mining activity?
Well, really and truly, like I say, I just can't remember for sure how it did affect the mines.
But back then, people our age, you know, we was thinking about other things.
We wasn't, you know what I mean.
Young people, they don't take things too serious, you know.
I guess it's a good thing they don't.
I find that they're taking you too seriously too young nowadays.
And a few of them don't take it serious enough.
You know what I mean?
You know what I mean?
They can get hooked on this dope or something, you know, and that's bad.
Or this drunk driving.
You see, my boy, the one who works for the IGC now, he was five years in the sheriff's office.
So he learned a few things.
He's seen lots of things that was pretty bad.
But we still got lots of young, good young people.
You bet.
You know, obviously now the mining camps are no longer there.
That's right.
Do you have any idea what happened to the Mexican families that were living there?
Have they moved out of property?
Well, I think they just scattered.
A few of them might have went back to old Mexico, had people there.
There's one Mexican who lived right up here a little ways.
We sure liked him.
He'd come down and talk to me sometimes.
I can't even call his name anymore, Sally Garcia, Garcia.
And he taught me a few Spanish words.
And he's buried over there next to the Spanish cemetery, Mexican cemetery.
And they just sort of scattered around.
Some of them farmed, and some of them went, a few of them.
You see, he come from old Mexico.
He could remember living in old Mexico.
But he could speak some English, you see.
Did he marry here?
I think his wife come from old Mexico.
She stayed at home most of the time.
She didn't go much.
Do you know of anybody specifically that grew up around the mines?
No, really, I don't.
I imagine they're over around there somewhere in places.
Some of them may be around Milano that grew up around the mines.
Do you know of anybody I might check, too?
Is that one thing I forgot?
They did have a doctor?
Oh, yes.
Well, I don't know.
That is for Big Lump now.
I don't know about the other camps.
This was Dr.
Rob Wallace.
He was a big man.
He lived at Rockdale.
That's right.
They'd call him, you know.
They had telephones back then, you know.
That's about all they did.
He'd come out.
Then he had a mine inspector, too.
I forgot who he was.
Seemed like one of my uncles was mine inspector for a while.
Cousin.
Mr. Bullock?
No.
Bullock.
Bullock.
He was mine inspector for a long time.
You're right.
But Rob Wallace was the company doctor there.
Now, how many mining camps he took, mines he took care of, I don't know, but he did.
When my granddaddy got hurt, that's the one that come out to him.
Did you take care of the children also, and the wives?
I don't think so.
I think it was just the minors.
Well, how did the wives and kids get medical attention?
Just like, they had no insurance.
They had no insurance.
They just had to pay their own.
They'd go into Rockville, and the doctor would come out?
Yeah, the doctor would come out there.
They had no hospital over there.
They had doctor's offices, and they'd come to your home.
So if the...
They'd come to him.
That's right.
That's right.
Sure did.
But my grandpa's chest was sort of crushed and he was broken up in here some.
It took him about a year, like I say, to die.
McCoy.
Daniel McCoy.
Mama's daddy.
That was about 1906.
Yeah, about 1906.
